<section label="sec-sov-method">
	<title>Separation of Variables (SOV) Method</title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Once you've verified that an equation is separable, solving it becomes a systematic process. Here's the step-by-step guide:
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<subsection xml:id="sov-steps">
		<title>Separation of Variables Steps</title>

		<assemblage xml:id="sov-method">
			<title>Separation of Variables</title>

			<p>
				<dl width="medium">
					<li xml:id="sov-step-1"><title>1. Verify Separable, Separate Variables</title>
						<p>Check that the equation is first-order</p>
						<p>If possible, put into separable form: <me>\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \cdot g(y)</me></p>
						<p>Separate <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> on opposite sides: <me>\frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = f(x)\ dx</me></p>
					</li>

					<li xml:id="sov-step-2"><title>2. Integrate</title>
						<p><me>\int \frac{1}{g(y)}\, dy = \int f(x)\, dx.</me></p>
					</li>

					<li xml:id="sov-step-3"><title>3. Solve for <m>y</m></title>
						<p>
							If possible, explicitly solve for <m>y</m>. If not, leave the solution in implicit form. Combine constants.
						</p>
					</li>

				</dl>
			</p>

		</assemblage>

		<proof xml:id="justification-split-dydx">
			<title> (Optional) Justification of separating <m>dy</m> &amp; <m>dx</m> in <m>\dfrac{dy}{dx}</m></title>

			<p>
				Although separating <m>dy</m> &amp; <m>dx</m> in <m>\sfrac{dy}{dx}</m> is mathematically invalid, it is a widely accepted shortcut in the SOV method. 
			</p>

			<p>
				To see why, start with the separable form,
				<me>
					\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x) \cdot g(y)
				</me>,
				and divide both sides by <m>g(y)</m>, leaving the derivative intact:
				<me>
					\frac{1}{g(y)}\ \frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)
				</me>.
			</p>

			<p>
				From here, integrate both sides with respect to <m>x</m>:
				<me>
					\int \frac{1}{g(y)}\ \frac{dy}{dx}\ dx = \int f(x)\ dx
				</me>.
			</p>

			<p>
				Since the product, <m>\sfrac{dy}{dx}\cdot dx</m>, is defined as the differential, <m>dy</m>, we can substitute it in to get the form of the integral you see in <xref ref="sov-step-2" text="custom">Step 2</xref>:
				<me>
					\int \frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = \int f(x)\ dx,
				</me>
				which justifies the informal splitting of <m>dy</m> and <m>dx</m> in the derivative, <m>\sfrac{dy}{dx}</m>.
			</p>

		</proof>

		<exercise label="sov-method-cyu-1">
			<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e> Reorder the Strategy</title>
				
			<statement>
				<p>
					Reorder the scrambled tasks used in the <xref ref="sov-method" text="title"/> method.
				</p>
			</statement>

			<feedback>
				<p>
					Review the <xref ref="sov-method" text="custom">SOV Method</xref>.
				</p>
			</feedback>

			<blocks>
				<block order="1">
					Verify first-order
				</block>
				<block order="2">
					<p>
						Verify separable form:
						<me>\frac{dy}{dx} = f(x)g(y)</me>
					</p>
				</block>
				<block order="3">
					<p>
						Separate variables:
						<me>\frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = f(x)\ dx</me>
					</p>
				</block>
				<block order="4">
					<me>\int \frac{1}{g(y)}\ dy = \int f(x)\ dx</me>
				</block>
				<block order="5">
						Apply integration techniques
				</block>
				<block order="6">
					Solve for <m>y</m> (if possible) &amp; combine constants
				</block>
			</blocks>

		</exercise>

		<p>
			Let's begin with a few warm-up problems to build confidence in using separation of variables. The examples that follow are intentionally straightforward, each equation is either already separable or requires minimal algebraic manipulation. As you work through them, focus on the 3-step strategy described in the <xref ref="sov-method" text="title"/> method.
		</p>

		<exercise label="sov-method-cyu-2">
			<title><e component="emoji">üìñ‚ùì</e> Review Separability</title>

			<statement>
				<p>Which of the following differential equations are separable?</p>
			</statement>

			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\quad\ds \frac{dy}{dx} = x e^y</m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>Is this the product of a function of <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>?</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement><m>\quad\ds \frac{dy}{dx} = \frac{x}{1 + y^2}</m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>Note: <m>\frac{x}{1 + y^2} = x \cdot \frac{1}{1 + y^2}</m>.</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad\ds \frac{dy}{dx} - y = x</m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Moving <m>y</m> over you get 
							<me>
								\frac{dy}{dx} = x + y
							</me>.
							Can a sum like this be converted into the form <m>f(x) \cdot g(y)</m>?
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement><m>\quad\ds y'' = \ln(x)\ln(y)</m></statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>Note, this is a second-order differential equation...</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>

		</exercise>

	</subsection>
	
	<subsection>
		<title>Warm-Up Examples</title>

		<p>Find the general solution for each equation.</p>
	
		<example xml:id="sov-method-example-1">

			<statement>
				<p>
					<m>
						\quad 1.\ \ \dfrac{dy}{dx} = x^4,\
						\quad 2.\ \ \dfrac{dy}{dx} = y^2
					</m>
				</p>
			</statement>

			<solution>

				<p>
					We'll solve these equations, side-by-side, clearly demonstrating each step of the <xref ref="sov-method" text="title"/> method.
				</p>
				
				<p><xref ref="sov-step-1" text="custom">Step 1</xref> - Verify separability &amp; separate variables:</p>

				<sidebyside widths="25% 30% 25%" valign="top" margins="2% 18%">
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\frac{dy}{dx} \amp = x^4 \cdot 1 \quad\checkmark
							</mrow>
							<mrow>dy \amp = x^4\ dx</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
					<p/>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>
								\frac{dy}{dx} \amp = 1 \cdot y^2 \quad\checkmark
							</mrow>
							<mrow>y^{-2}\ dy \amp = dx</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<p><xref ref="sov-step-2" text="custom">Step 2</xref> - Integrate:</p>

				<sidebyside widths="25% 30% 25%" valign="top" margins="2% 18%">
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>\int dy \amp = \int x^4\ dx</mrow>
							<mrow>y + c_1 \amp = \frac{1}{5}x^5 + c_2</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
					<p/>
					<p>
						<md>
							<mrow>\int y^{-2}\ dy \amp = \int dx</mrow>
							<mrow>-\frac{1}{y} + c_1 \amp = x + c_2</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<p><xref ref="sov-step-3" text="custom">Step 3</xref> - Solve for <m>y</m> and combine constants:</p>

				<sidebyside widths="25% 5% 55%" valign="top" margins="1%">
					<p>
						<me>
							\boxed{y = \frac{1}{5}x^5 + c}
						</me>
					</p>
					<p/>
					<p>
						<me>
							\frac{1}{y} = -x + c \ \Rightarrow\ \boxed{y = \frac{1}{-x + c}}
						</me>
					</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<p>where <m>c = c_2 - c_1</m> in both general solutions.</p>

			</solution>

		</example>

		<example xml:id="sov-method-example-2">

			<statement>
				<p><m>\quad\dfrac{dy}{dx} + \dfrac{x}{y^2} = 0</m></p>
			</statement>

			<solution>

				<p>
					<xref ref="sov-step-1" text="custom">Step 1</xref> - Verify separability &amp; separate variables:
					<md>
						<mrow>\frac{dy}{dx} \amp = -\frac{x}{y^2} = (-x)\cdot\frac{1}{y^2} \quad\checkmark</mrow>
						<mrow>y^2\ dy \amp = -x\ dx.</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					<xref ref="sov-step-2" text="custom">Step 2</xref> - Integrate:
					<md>
						<mrow>\int y^2\ dy \amp = \int -x\ dx</mrow>
						<mrow>\frac{y^3}{3} + c_1 \amp = -\frac{x^2}{2} + c_2</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					<xref ref="sov-step-3" text="custom">Step 3</xref> - Combine constants and solve explicitly for <m>y</m>:
					<me>
						\frac{y^3}{3} = -\frac{x^2}{2} + c \quad\Rightarrow\quad \boxed{y = \left(-\frac{3}{2}x^2 + c\right)^{1/3}}.
					</me>
				</p>

			</solution>

		</example>

		<p>Solve the initial-value problem.</p>

		<example label="sov-method-initial-value-problem">

			<statement>
				<p><m>z' - 1 = z^2, \quad z(4) = 9</m></p>
			</statement>

			<solution>
				<p>
					This differential equation is first order and separable since
				</p>
				<sidebyside widths="80% 20%" valign="bottom" margins="0% 0%">
					<p>
							<md>
							<mrow> z' - 1	\amp = z^2 </mrow>
							<mrow> z'		\amp = z^2 + 1 = \big( 1 \big) \big( z^2 + 1 \big) \quad\checkmark</mrow>
						</md>
					</p>
					<p>Separable</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<p>
					Next, we separate and integrate: 
				</p>

				<sidebyside widths="80% 20%" valign="middle" margins="0% 0%">
					<p><me>\frac{1}{z^2+1}dz = 1\ dt</me></p>
					<p>Separate</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<sidebyside widths="80% 20%" valign="middle" margins="0% 0%">
					<p><me> \int\frac{1}{z^2+1}\ dz = \int 1\ dt </me></p>
					<p>Integrate</p>
				</sidebyside>

				<sidebyside widths="80% 20%" valign="middle" margins="0% 0%">
					<p><me> \arctan z = t + c </me></p>
					<p></p>
				</sidebyside>

				<p>
					So, the general solution is
					<me> z = \tan(t+c) </me>.
				</p>

				<p>
					Applying <m>z(4) = 9</m> to the general solution, we get an equation for <m>c</m>:
					<md>
						<mrow>	9 = \tan(4+c) \implies	\amp\ \arctan(9) = 4 + c	</mrow>
						<mrow>							\amp\ \arctan(9) - 4 = c	</mrow>
					</md>
				</p>

				<p>
					Therefore, 
					<me>
						z = \tan(t + \arctan(9) - 4)
					</me>
					is the particular solution to the intial-valued problem.
					<fn>
						<p>
							Be cautious about rewriting constants in decimal form. For instance, if you approximate <m>\arctan(9) - 4 \approx -2.54</m>, the solution becomes:
							<me>z = \tan(t - 2.54),</me>
							which may not exactly satisfy the original initial condition due to rounding errors. It's usually better to leave constants in exact form.
						</p>
					</fn>
				</p>
			</solution>
		</example>

	</subsection>

</section>